rComments: Someone should remind Kim that she is teaching literature, not womens studies. I hope you enjoy relating every topic to the mistreatment of women and minorities, because that is the class in a nutshell. Prepare for another quarter pandering to the professors agenda. She has a bully pulpit and is not afraid to use it.

Kim was absolutely amazing. I have taken several classes with her and she is, by far, one of the BEST Literature professors here at UCSC. She is passionate and eloquent. She is also open to holding discussions with students both in and out of class. Her lectures are clear and easy to follow. I would definitely recommend her.

I've taken classes with Kim before and so I was pretty stoked for her Vamps class. Definitely, a ton of reading (some very difficult ones, too), but she actually worked with the students to take out some readings (yay for considerate professors). Kim is also very willing to help outside of class and she's just ... super duper amazing!

I took the Academic Challenge program class for first-years this spring quarter, and I have to say, Kim is a fantastic professor. Although the readings are rough, she's passionate about what she's teaching; I definitely recommend Vamps with her because of her background in mythical creatures and literature. She's great, and it was a fun time.
She was a great teacher. The readings were ALOT, but TA's helped out. Never will regret taking this class. It gives a new perspective in some ways.

Kim is an AMAZING professor who teaches a fascinating subject. This was my favorite class. There was loads of reading and if you didn't do it, you wouldn't do well, but it was a great class. I looked forward to the lectures and actually enjoyed writing the essays because the topic was so interesting.

very hard grader. her TA's are really hard grader. If English is not your first language . NEVER take this class. thought that it would be a easy GE but no! a lot a lot of reading. 3 essay for the whole quarter. really bad!

Kim is a brilliant professor. Her eloquence make her lectures compelling along with her ability to clarify esoteric theories and concepts. She is so smart I am convinced she knows the meaning of life.

Kim is a brilliant professor. Her lectures are compelling bc she is eloquent and able to explain the esoteric theories and concepts clearly. She is so knowledgeable and I am convinced she knows the meaning of life.
Interesting class, but far more reading than I expected and very detailed, but good all in all.

An incredible teacher who is passionate about the subject and teaching in general. Can tell that she spends ample time preparing and crafting interesting and thought-provoking lectures. One of my favorite classes!

Feminist Transformations of Fairy Tales... VERY interesting topic, and very competent professor. Kim is very down-to-earth and funny, yet also very professional. The reader was an interesting blend of fiction and literary theory. Downside: some lectures and articles were VERY difficult...leading to minimal contributions from students.

Even though I didn't agree with her ideas most of the time, at least she didn't dumb-down her material to fit the very low scholastic standards of our time. She's a good lecturer (i.e. a hard yet cogent lecturer). She'll make you think a lot and work for your grade. People who are looking for an easy ride should steer clear of this class.
Difficult and brash teacher- not passionate about the material and devoid of people skills. Difficult to approach and unnecessarily difficult for an introductory course. Avoid at all costs.

Your grade in the class is based on how well you can regurgitate her extremely one-sided opinions on American politics.  Of course being in in Santa Cruz, 70% of the class ate it up like she was the all knowing messiah.  The midterms require you to recall minute details from readings.  Good riddance to the AMST major if it's more of this America ba

Kim is a professor for serious students who care about their education, and her lectures are consistently engaging for people who consistently pay attention.  What you put into this class is literally what you get out of it, so people looking to float on through without learning a thing will have both the lack of knowledge and grade to prove it.

I loved her class. People who complain about it just weren't willing to do the work that was needed. I slacked off on a lot of the readings before the midterm and got a 59%, but then I caught up on the readings and ended up getting a b+. She makes amazing points and opened my eyes to a lot about American culture that I never noticed
People who don't like her just dislike the fact that if you slack off in this class then youre grade will go down for sure. she's really smart, and your grade will reflect your effort directly

It's absurd that she is having every student in a 300 student class, enter the final only knowing 15% of their grade.  85% is entirely left up to the oh so competent TAs, and her strict grading policy. We won't know what we get on individual things such as the project she never returned, so we have no way of double checking or challenging (donttake

At first, I thought this class would be interesting and a good way to knock of a ge while simultaneously taking two difficult major classes. turns out i have to put more effort into this class and my other classes are suffering as a result! practically everyone failed the midterm so now the final is 50%, do not take this class!
She's less accurate than Fox News. Seriously, this class was ten weeks on why america is a horrible country. I'd have learned far more watching the History Channel or MSNBC.

Kim is very personable, but she doesnt use slides or anything she just talks and talks. Lectures arent really necessary because she basically goes off of the readings. midterm was really nitpicky with things we were supposed to remember that were really obscure and random. If you remember pointless facts this class will be a breeze. TAs were good.

LOVED HER. She was my first writing professor at UCSC. She is open to new ideas, and she is very kind and understanding. Participation is KEY. I guarantee if you raise your hand, she'll raise your grade. Fun, laid back, and easy. I highly recommend her. (P.S... do the Oakes 4.0 card)

Kim is an amazing professor who still manages to be very humble and approachable.  I took the Amst. "W" course with her.  I felt like my grasp of key amst. concepts really improved during this course, and she was absolutely wonderful and facilitating great discussions.

She's extremely helpful. Intelligent and has experience in her field. I took a feminism and motherhood class with her and she brought in a lot of material I had never been introduced to before and I was a senior. I'm sad I only got to take one class with her.

Lau is a very personable professor. Explains concepts well in class, and responds promptly to e-mail inquiries. Interesting materials for the class, although some were confusing and seemed irrelevant before discussed in the broader context of the class.
Boring, disorganized, and unprepared. it felt like high school. She's got her likes and dislikes, and if you don't share them, you're out of luck.  Not an objective presentation of material.
